body:
First, lets review the first amendment; 
"Congress shall make no law respecting an establishment of religion, or prohibiting the free exercise thereof; or abridging the freedom of speech, or of the press; or the right of the people peaceably to assemble, and to petition the government for a redress of grievances." Basically this is saying the part of the government that makes laws (congress) can not make any laws prohibiting your freedom of religion, assembly, speech, press, or protesting the government. 

Now, what does this have to do with League?
When people get in trouble for toxicity or whatever they almost always go to the "my freedom of speeechhh!" claim, which is incorrect. The first amendment stops the government from restricting your freedoms (though even that has limits) however it does NOT restrict private locations or businesses from this, this is why you can be fired because you talk about politics at work while on hours, or kicked out of a business for calling people names. The same applies to online accounts, ie. League of Legends. Riot is *allowing* you to use one of their accounts, this is like *allowing* you to enter the building to do your business. So, all in all, Riot Games has every right to ban you for using "toxic" language, whether you agree with it or not. 
